{{Infobox person | name = Ebba Lund | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 22 September 1923 | birth_place = Denmark | death_date = 21 June 1999 | death_place = | nationality = Danish | other_names = | occupation = Resistance Fighter | years_active = 1942-1944 | known_for = | notable_works = }}
'''Ebba Lund''' (22 September 1923 – 21 June 1999) was a [[Danish resistance movement|Danish Resistance fighter]] during [[World War II]] and a scientist.
== Resistance work == Lund began her resistance work in 1942, two years after the German invasion of Denmark. Her work initially consisted of publishing illegal underground newspapers with her sister.<ref name="auto">{{cite book|last=Atwood|first=Kathryn J.|title=Women Heroes of World War II|location=Chicago|publisher=Chicago Review Press|date=2011 |isbn=9781556529610 |page=159}}</ref> Lund worked for ''Frit Danmark,''the most popular clandestine newspaper.<ref name="auto"/>
When the Danish government was dissolved and Nazi Germany took over, Lund joined [[Holger Danske (resistance group)|Holger Danske]], a sabotage-oriented Resistance group.<ref name="auto1">{{cite book|last=Atwood|first=Kathryn J.|title=Women Heroes of World War II|location=Chicago|publisher=Chicago Review Press|date=2011 |isbn=9781556529610 |page=162}}</ref> The first task was to procure fishing boats to take Jews to Sweden. Safe houses were set up for Jews until they could safely be taken to Sweden, and Lund's own house was used as a safe house.<ref name="auto1"/> During her rescue operations, Lund became known as the Girl with the Red Cap or Red Riding Hood because of the red hat she woreto signal the Jews to be escorted to look for her.<ref>{{cite book|last=Atwood|first=Kathryn J.|title=Women Heroes of World War II|location=Chicago|publisher=Chicago Review Press|date=2011 |isbn=9781556529610 |page=163}}</ref> The Resistance did not only aid Jewish individuals, however; they also assisted defecting German soldiers and other Resistance members.<ref name="nytimes.com">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/09/28/world/danes-commemorate-rescue-of-jews-from-nazis.html|title=Danes Commemorate Rescue of Jews From Nazis|date=28 September 1993|work=The New York Times}}</ref>
The Holger Danske group helped save 700-800 Jews in only a few weeks by offering means of escape.<ref name="auto2">{{cite book|last=Atwood|first=Kathryn J.|title=Women Heroes of World War II|location=Chicago|publisher=Chicago Review Press|date=2011 |isbn=9781556529610 |page=164}}</ref> Lund herself had a hand in about 500 of these missions.<ref name="nytimes.com"/> Lund managed to escape arrest because, at a time when many of her fellow Resistance workers were being arrested, she was hospitalized with blood poisoning. In 1944, Lund became pregnant and withdrew entirely from Resistance work.<ref name="auto3">{{cite web|url=http://bibliotek.science.ku.dk/life150/forskere/ebba-lund/|title=Ebba Lund|first=Knud|last=Høgsberg|date=31 January 2014|publisher=}}</ref>
== Later life == After the war, Lund studied [[chemical engineering]] and [[immunology]]. She did important research on the [[polio]] virus in response to a polio epidemic in Denmark at the time.<ref name="auto3"/><ref name="auto2"/> Lund became the head of the Department of Virology and Immunology at the [[Royal Veterinary and Agricultural University]] in Copenhagen.<ref name="auto2"/> She was the first female professor at this institution at the time.<ref name="auto3"/> Lund was an incredibly prolific scientist; she published 124 works in her lifetime, including 84 in English, as well as a lecture series and other content.<ref name="auto3"/>
In 1975, Lund became a [[Knight of the Dannebrog]] and in 1984 was appointed to knight in the first degree.<ref name="auto3"/> In 1985, Lund received the Ebbe Muncks Award for her service in the Resistance.<ref name="auto3"/>
Lund died in 1999.<ref name="auto2"/>
