Theo Botha first decided to pursue shareholder activism after an investment in a small life insurance company ([[The Sage Group]]).<ref name=sagesuit>{{Cite web | last = Hazelhurst | first = Ethel | title = Attorney considers lawsuit against Sage on behalf of minority shareholders | work = [[AllAfrica.com]] | location = | publisher = | date = 3 August 2005 | url = http://allafrica.com/stories/200508030338.html | accessdate = 2010-11-29 }} </ref> The company was making huge losses in the United States that it refused to disclose to the South African shareholders.<ref name=tycoontoes> {{Cite news | last = Newmarch | first = Jocelyn | title = Keeping Tycoons on Their Toes | newspaper = Mail & Guardian Online | location = Cape Town, South Africa | publisher = [[Mail & Guardian]] | date = 10 May 2007 | url = http://www.mg.co.za/article/2007-05-10-keeping-tycoons-on-their-toes | accessdate = 2010-11-29 }} </ref>
In a press interview it was found that "Botha doesn’t appear to be making money off this enterprise; in most instances he buys only one share."<ref name=bashfulactivist>{{Cite web | last = Rose | first = Rob | title = Bashful activist raises hackles of corporate SA | work = [[AllAfrica.com]] | location = | pages = | publisher = | date = 9 February 2007 | url = http://www.businessday.co.za/Articles/TarkArticle.aspx?ID=2552425 | accessdate = 2010-11-29 }} </ref>
==Activism== Botha's usual approach is not unlike his first encounter with Sage in which all he did was pose a few questions which usually make the companies in question edgy.{{Citation needed|date=January 2011}} He spends time going through company financial reports to note discrepancies which he will use to compile his questions which he asks during company AGM's.{{Citation needed|date=January 2011}}
